     <h2><font color="#000080"><!-- 2004-09-02 -->
	 
	 OOX-ODF: Oh the Outrage, the Stridence, the Indignities, the Inhumanity, ...
	 </font>
     </h2>
    

	<p>
    <div style="clear:both;"></div><blockquote> <p><em>If we are seeing “interoperability theater,” the public and the publics’ documents will be its hostages.&nbsp; I don’t want that to happen.&nbsp; A truce, and an effort to have interoperability that works, would be far more rewarding.&nbsp; Peaceful coexistence strikes me as a desirable state.<br></em>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; -- <a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2007/03/oox-odf-why-have-peace-when-you-can.asp"><em>Orcmid's Lair</em>, 2007-03-16</a></p></blockquote> <p>We are seeing conversations and posturing reminiscent of the cold war, the "axis of evil" proclamations, and other excesses of global politics.&nbsp; You'd think the stakes were civilization as we know it.&nbsp; I suspect many of the participants believe exactly that.&nbsp; All I can say is, "Follow the money."&nbsp; Then get a grip.</p> <center> <div class="wlWriterSmartContent" id="0767317B-992E-4b12-91E0-4F059A8CECA8:2f39de98-2427-450f-9f08-d4f356531941" contenteditable="false" style="padding-right: 0px; display: inline; padding-left: 0px; padding-bottom: 0px; margin: 0px; padding-top: 0px">Technorati Tags: <a href="http://technorati.com/tags/orcmid" rel="tag">orcmid</a>, <a href="http://technorati.com/tags/ECMA-379" rel="tag">ECMA-379</a>, <a href="http://technorati.com/tags/OOXML" rel="tag">OOXML</a>, <a href="http://technorati.com/tags/ODF" rel="tag">ODF</a>, <a href="http://technorati.com/tags/ISO/IEC%20DIS%2029500" rel="tag">ISO/IEC DIS 29500</a>, <a href="http://technorati.com/tags/ISO%20JTC1%20ballot" rel="tag">ISO JTC1 ballot</a></div></center> <p></p> <p>I&nbsp;was recently asked "What's happening with Orcmid?&nbsp; He's pretty silent on&nbsp;OOXML and the run-up to the JTC1&nbsp;ballot-period deadline."&nbsp; Mostly, I have found little to comment about that I haven't commented on already.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p> <p><strong>I favor adoption of&nbsp;an ISO&nbsp;standard for OOXML</strong>.&nbsp; I am&nbsp;generally&nbsp;aligned with the running commentary that <a href="http://www.oreillynet.com/pub/au/1712">Rick Jelliffe</a> has provided over the course of the ballot period.&nbsp; I'm content with <a href="http://www.oreillynet.com/xml/blog/2007/08/my_recommendation_on_office_op.html">his recommendation</a> too.&nbsp; As a bystander, I can provide no fact-based information on the ISO JTC1 process better than that.&nbsp; I am certainly in no position to counter all of the outrage that is splattered all over the&nbsp;web and the trade press on the conduct of the ballot period that ends today.&nbsp; </p> <p>From my perspective, the OOXML and ODF efforts are merely the start of an important journey where we improve our mutual understanding of what it takes to operate with standard document formats in collaboration, interchange, and preservation using different implementations (of the same or different formats).&nbsp; This is important work, and we need these standards as a starting point.&nbsp; It's a long and winding road ahead, and we need to have as many positive contributions as can be found.</p> <p><strong>Concerning&nbsp;the inflammatory statements that are happily exaggerated and perpetuated, I have nothing to offer but my disdain</strong>.&nbsp; There,&nbsp;that's done.&nbsp; Now what?</p> <p>It is not possible to prove negatives, and if I could I am not the one with the facts.&nbsp; So any response would be simply&nbsp;opposition of bluster with more bluster.&nbsp; I am a proponent of light, not heat.&nbsp; Countering outrage with more outrage is not getting us anywhere.&nbsp; In particular, what can one do when&nbsp;those outside of the process allow&nbsp;their credulity&nbsp;to erupt in&nbsp;echoing outrage without any determinations of fact (my <a href="http://weblogs.macromedia.com/jd/archives/2007/09/ooxml_overview.cfm" rel="nofollow">one example</a> that I am willing to link to), and technology writers&nbsp;abandon investigation and exploration for understanding&nbsp;in favor of their&nbsp;own outrage and expression of ridicule (my <a href="http://www.eweek.com/article2/0,1759,2178222,00.asp?kc=EWRSS03129TX1K0000616" rel="nofollow">other pet example</a>).</p> <p>I&nbsp;do want to provide some link love to&nbsp;Matthew Aslett's&nbsp;article "<a href="http://www.businessreviewonline.com/os/archives/2007/08/when_the_standa.html">When the Standards Are Low, No One Wins</a>."&nbsp; Matt says, in anticipation of the ballot&nbsp;that ends&nbsp;today, that</p> <blockquote> <p>"The approvals process has been one of the most petty, underhand, deceitful, and childish events I have had the misfortune to witness during ten years in the technology industry. Whatever the outcome there is little to be proud of."</p></blockquote> <p>Notice how everyone who cites this quotation (often without linking to the full article)&nbsp;or comments on this post thinks this is an indictment of Microsoft alone.&nbsp; Also, he catalogs the allegations that have been made, he does not do anything to claim the facts beyond the obvious one that this is a terrible situation.&nbsp; With that much reality distortion&nbsp;by those&nbsp;who&nbsp;appeal to&nbsp;this article as&nbsp;evidence for truth of their allegations, what can I possibly add that won't come off as more of the same (whether supporting a different "truth" or not)?</p> <p><strong>All right, enough of this</strong>.&nbsp; I do have more observations to contribute around the problems of document-format standards, how we achieve interoperability, and what is needed for conformance to be meaningful to people with work to do.&nbsp; But that is separate from the ISO JTC1 process, however today's completed stage is found to have turned out.</p> <p><strong>With regard to the interval from submission to ECMA and our arrival at this point, here's a summary of previous materials that I find to be relevant today</strong>.&nbsp; This is the easiest way to understand what I value, what I think is important, and how one can go about reconciling these differences in a professional, considerate manner.</p> <hr>  <dl> <dt><a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2007/04/open-standards-implementation-i.asp">Open Standards Implementation, I: Celebrating Massachusetts</a>.&nbsp; <em>Orcmid's Lair</em> (web log), 2007-04-18.  <dd>There's an exchange with Rob Weir in the comments and my colleague Bill Anderson makes an important observation. This is my most-recent commentary related to the OOX-ODF jihad. I now have as many as four more pieces in draft. I suspended posting when the controversy over allowing OOXML in the 2007 update to the Enterprise Technology Reference Model arose. That issue is resolved for now and I will pick up on this sequence at my leisure.&nbsp;&nbsp; The importance of this appraisal, for me, is to show how <a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2007/03/oox-odf-taming-guerilla-bob-sutor-just.asp">reason and prudence</a> lead to&nbsp;competent, professional outcomes in the face of unexpected public scrutiny and controversy.&nbsp; It also provides some concrete reality&nbsp;in opposition to the sloganeering about the "miracle in Massachusetts."<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  <dt><a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2007/04/oox-odf-national-body-review-comments.asp">OOX-ODF: National Body Review Comments on Office Open XML File Formats, ISO/IEC DIS 29500 (ECMA-376).</a>&nbsp; <em>Orcmid's Lair</em> (web log), 2007-04-18.  <dd>In all of the he-said, she-said back and forth, it is extremely important to look at the actual documents.&nbsp; These materials are the basis for the review and ballot period that ends today, September 2, 2007.&nbsp; I'll not comment on the result tally and the comments that have been submitted until the smoke has cleared and all materials are available.&nbsp; Perhaps the most remarkable aspect of the run-up to availability of this material were the <a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2007/03/oox-odf-ecma-response-to-iso-comments-i.asp">different interpretations</a> that were made without providing access to the sources.&nbsp; Perhaps the most remarkable event in the&nbsp;time since&nbsp;is the degree to which the antagonism became more strident and inflammatory with terrible assertions of misconduct of many kinds.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  <dt><a href="http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2007/03/why-not-suitability-of-rtf-for-open.asp">Why Not .rtfx?</a>&nbsp; <em>Professor von Clueless in the Blunder Dome</em> (web log), 2007-03-26.&nbsp;  <dd>This was inspired by my noticing that Massachusetts had added RTF to version 3.6 of the Enterprise Technology Reference Model, the specifications under which the Commonwealth's Information Technology Division carries out its policies for preference to open specifications.&nbsp; Rob&nbsp;Weir contributes a comment.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;  <dt><a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2007/03/oox-odf-why-have-peace-when-you-can.asp">OOX-ODF: Why Have Peace When You Can Have War?</a>&nbsp; <em>Orcmid's Lair</em> (web log), 2007-03-16.  <dd>"It sometimes appears that it is even more objectionable when Microsoft takes steps to cure a situation that has been the subject of previous complaints.&nbsp; I’ve not found a straightforward way to account for this amusing aspect of human nature at its most frustrating." There's more about all of the energy invested in keeping the fight alive, something that has me wonder what the fight is really about.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;  <dt><a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2007/02/oox-odf-and-mystery-document-flavors.asp">OOX-ODF and the Mystery Document Flavors</a>.&nbsp; <em>Orcmid's Lair</em> (web log), 2007-02-11.  <dd>Where I do a little detective work to figure out how the ECMA folk produced two forms of the identical material and that gave rise to automatic suspicions that ECMA-379 had been altered after adoption. I don't think ECMA will raise a lightning rod like this again.&nbsp; More seriously was the degree to which OOX adversaries announced their darkest fears without doing some simple homework to realize that there is no difference, no harm, and they simply invested way too much in tying reviews to PDF page numbering instead of the official document page numbers. Sheesh. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  <dt><a href="http://orcmid.com/blog/2007/02/oox-odf-danger-of-finding-only-what.asp">OOX-ODF: The Danger of Finding What You're Looking For</a>.&nbsp; <em>Orcmid's Lair</em> (web log), 2007-02-11.  <dd>There is a well-known blind spot by which we continue to see what we are looking for, failing to look deeper and recognize when matters are not as our cynicism has us blindly transform&nbsp;into believed&nbsp;facts.&nbsp; I use two examples from the reviews of ECMA-376 during the ISO contradiction-review period. <br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  <dt><a href="http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2005/12/without-context-every-open-format.asp">Without Context, Every Open-Format Standard Is the Best</a>.&nbsp; <em>Professor von Clueless in the Blunder Dome</em> (web log), 2005-12-20.  <dd>At this point, OOXML&nbsp;was submitted to ECMA&nbsp;and the licensing issues that colored the earlier antagonism to OOXML would appear to be resolved.&nbsp; Nay-sayers will continue to&nbsp;fear hidden patent traps along with their expectation that Microsoft will extend their implementation of OOXML into a proprietary prison. There being no way to disprove a negative, and having no way to speak for Microsoft, the recent shift of the conversation to a new strident level is one that I don't partake in.&nbsp; For people who see technical show-stoppers, I will continue to point out that&nbsp;the same yardsticks can and should be applied to ODF and OOXML equally.&nbsp; We&nbsp;should be concentrating our energies into getting experience and making repairs, not tearing down the specification we don't intend to use.&nbsp; This post is an argument against disembodied, decontextualized claims of advantage and disadvantage between ODF and OOXML.&nbsp; Those arguments,&nbsp;primarily from those arguing that OOXML is simply unnecessary at best or evil at worst,&nbsp;simply impeach the&nbsp;objectivity of those who&nbsp;make such claims.&nbsp; It is striking&nbsp;to me how much the OOXML supporters talk about what people are doing with OOXML and what&nbsp;benefit they see in it.&nbsp; ODF advocates would be&nbsp;better served by similar attentions&nbsp;to ODF benefits and repairs and less fixation on OOXML.<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;  <dt><a href="http://orcmid.com/BlunderDome/clueless/2005/10/magical-thinking-and-universal.asp">Magical Thinking and the Universal Document Elixir</a>.&nbsp; <em>Professor von Clueless in the Blunder Dome</em> (web log), 2005-10-17.  <dd>This is where I&nbsp;challenge&nbsp;an assumption that still goes uncorrected (especially in the technical press) that document formats (especially the ODF) are universal in the sense that one can do everything another can do that is of any importance.&nbsp; Ben Langhinrichs makes a nicely-balanced observation in the comments.&nbsp; Stephen Walli has a <a href="http://stephesblog.blogs.com/my_weblog/2007/08/office-open-xml.html">recent post</a> that points out how difficult this is with separate implementations against <em>the same</em> document-format specification.&nbsp; Adopters of ODF-supporting software should take heed ... and get busy.</dd></dl> <p><strong>I first entered this discussion</strong> over the unbalanced disputation around licensing issues.&nbsp; Those issues should be past us, despite the continued claims of proprietary submarines lurking in ECMA-376.&nbsp; I also found it necessary to dispute the completeness of ODF for unreserved embrace.&nbsp; The problem of ODF under-specification and the absence of a reasonable conformance condition and means for asserting conformance remains.&nbsp; This material, last&nbsp;revised in 2005-12-23, reflects neither the ODF 1.1 revisions (which don't change these observations) nor the final ECMA-376 treatment of conformance.&nbsp; Today, the value is mainly in <a href="http://orcmid.com/writings/2005/06/w050601b.htm#Table3-1">Table 3-1</a>, which could use some additional clean-ups whenever I get around to providing a much-needed repaving for this material:</p> <p>Dennis E. Hamilton.&nbsp; <a href="http://orcmid.com/writings/2005/06/w050601b.htm">Microsoft's IP-Infringement Specter</a>: <a href="http://orcmid.com/writings/2005/06/w050601g.htm">Continuing Toward Adoption</a>, Writings folio W050601g version 0.81, 2005-12-23.&nbsp; <em>Orcmid's Lair</em> (web site).&nbsp;</p> <hr>  <p><small>[<strong>update 2007-09-03T17:00Z</strong>:&nbsp;I fix up two more difficult passages in my annotated links.&nbsp; Also, in my response to&nbsp;Zaine I should mention that I also sat in on the Open Formula work until it was absorbed back into the OASIS ODF TC.&nbsp; Zaine also&nbsp;claims, on his web site, that ODF is a universal format.&nbsp; I, of course, don't believe there is any such thing, in theory and especially in practice.&nbsp; That's worth its own post.<br>&nbsp;</small><small><strong>update 2007-09-03T01:45Z</strong>: In some of my annotations to older links, I found some of the statements to be clumsy and I repaired the ones that poked me in the eye.&nbsp; I like the restatements better.&nbsp; You might not.<br></small><small>&nbsp;<strong>update 2007-09-03T00:22Z:</strong> I went through and checked all of the hyperlinks in this text.&nbsp; One of them was broken.<br></small><small>&nbsp;<strong>update 2007-09-02T23:35Z</strong>: I saw some troubling phrases that I cleaned up and then also noticed that I had one of my&nbsp;own blog titles wrong.&nbsp; Situation normal ... ]</small></p><div style="clear:both; padding-bottom:0.25em"></div>
    </p>
